arratives of British influence, Tamarkin highlights a more intricate culture of American response, one that included Whig elites, college students, radical democrats, urban immigrants, and African Americans. Ultimately, Anglophila argues that that the love of Britain was not simply a fetish or form of shame-a release from the burdens of American culture-but an anachronistic structure of attachement in which U.S. Identity was lived in other languages of national expression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDemocracyxSocial aspectsxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aDemocracyxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitical culturexHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aPolitical culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPopular culturexHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPublic opinionxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aPublic opinionzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226789439423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226789439.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles